The course examines the size of the public sector in Estonia and other countries, analyses the causes of the government intervention into the economy (market failures, income redistribution, stabilisation of the economy), the forms of intervention (taxes, regulations etc) and the problems accompanying interventions (i.e. government failures). Also the roles of the central and local governments and there relations are examined.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of this course is to discuss the necessities, possibilities and consequences of the public sector intervention into the economy.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Students who pass the course: 1) know the basic concepts and implications of public sector economics  2) identify standard situations when government intervention into the economy is needed, know basic policy instruments that government has for intervention and can discuss their suitability in standard cases 3) can analyze standard cases for government intervention and the main consequences of different policy instruments with the help of graphical models 4) understand that there are no universal best solutions to problems because the suitability of a solution may depend on different circumstances including the value judgements prevailing in the society
